Question 1

Part A

In this part, we are asked to visualize the eight gesture patterns in a 3D scatter plot. To perform this task, I utilized the data collected through a single three-axis accelerometer. The collected data covers the acceleration information,therefore, by calculating cumulative sum of acceleration over time, I obtained the velocity vector for each axis. Then, calculating cumulative sum of these velocity vectors, I obtained the location information in three-axis. The plot_gesture function takes two input. First input tells the function which gesture type will be visualized. In other words, it takes values from 1 to 8. On the other hand, second input selects a particular observation with desired gesture type. Note that, we have many observations for each gesture type.

Plots

You can find plots for some different gesture types below. In the plots, while green points denote the start, red points the end.

Part B

In this part, we are asked to apply k-nearest neighbor classifier to predict the type of a gesture by considering similarity in the available acceleration information. After combining the information from each axis, we have 315*3=945 feature to represent each observation. Note that we have also class information(from 1 to 8) for each observation. Therefore, each observation is represented by 946 columns in total.

As a similarity measure, I utilized the euclidian distance in one approach, and manhattan distance in the other. knn function in FNN package uses directly euclidian distance while classifying the new points. On the other hand, kknn function in kknn package uses Minkowski distance. For Minkowski distance, if we set distance parameter as 1 in the kknn function, we can utilize Manhattan distance while classifying.

You can see how Minowski Distance is calculated below. To obtain Manhattan distance, set p=1.

\[MinkowskiDistance=(\sum_ {i=1}^n |x_i-y_i|^p)^{1/p} \]

Since the distance evaluation is required in both of the methods, the 945 feature is scaled before applying the methods. Finally, I need to determine the optimal value of k. By applying 10-fold cross-validation on the training set, I measured the accuracy with different k values with two distance measure. As a result of this, best k values are determined for each method among four candidates(k=1,3,5,7).

Question 2

In this question, we are asked to construct a logistic regression model on the training data using fused lasso penalties. By analyzing a time series data, we will clasify observations. In penalized regression approaches, the following objective function is minimized.

\[L(\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\beta)= |y-X\beta|^2+\lambda_2|\beta|^2+\lambda_1(\sum_ {i=2}^p |\beta_j-\beta_{j-1}|) \]

In the equation above, \(\lambda_2\) will be set to 0. In this way, we will obtain a model with fused lasso penalties. To perform this task,optL1 function in penalized package is utilized. This function does the cross validation itself to choose a \(\lambda_1\) value that minimizing the error. Since coefficients are penalized, it is necessary to scale input data.

The code below constructs the model on training set, then measure its performance on the test set. Since it is a classification problem, the variable type of response is changed as factor. Decision threshold is set to 0.5. In our training data, there is an imbalance between two classes. However, stratification is not applied while conducting cross validation, which is a drawback of this function. By executing the two lines of code, we can see this fact easily. (Note that ecg_model is the obtained model via optL1)

foldd<-as.data.table(ecg_model\(fold) imbalance<-ecg_train_class[which(foldd\)V1==1),]
